{"batchcomplete":"","query":{"normalized":[{"from":"bucket","to":"Bucket"}],"pages":{"352453":{"pageid":352453,"ns":0,"title":"Bucket","revisions":[{"contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{About|the physical container}}\n[[File:Gotland-Bottarve Museumshof 07.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Water well buckets]]\nA '''bucket''' or '''pail''' is typically a watertight, vertical [[Cylinder (geometry)|cylinder]] or [[Truncation (geometry)|truncated]] [[Cone (geometry)|cone]], with an open top and a flat bottom, attached to a semicircular carrying [[handle (grip)|handle]] called the ''[[Bail handle|bail]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bucket|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/bucket|publisher=Merriam-Webster|accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book  |editor1-first=Stuart |editor1-last=Flexner |editor2-first=:epmpre |editor2-last=Hauck  |title=Random House Unabridged Dictionary  p|type=hardcover |edition=second |year=1993 |month= |origyear=1987 |publisher=Random House |location=New York |isbn=0-679-42917-4 |page=271 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Japanese Edo Bousui.jpg|right|250px]]\n\nBuilding materials and solvents have been packaged in large metal pails, but in recent decades plastic buckets have been greatly favored.  Plastic buckets have more uses due to the popularity of plastic for food products and the tendency of metal pails to rust. \n\n==Types and uses==\n\nThere are many types of buckets;\n* A water bucket is used to carry [[water]]\n* Household and garden buckets are often used for carrying liquids and granular products\n* Elaborate ceremonial or ritual buckets in [[bronze]], [[ivory]] or other materials are found in several ancient or medieval cultures and are sometimes known by the Latin for bucket, [[Situla (vessel)|situla]]\n* Large scoops or buckets are attached to [[loader (equipment)|loader]]s and [[telehandler]]s for agricultural and earthmoving purposes\n* [[Crusher#Crusher_Bucket|Crusher bucket]]s attached to excavators are used for crushing and recycling material in the Construction Industry\n* A [[lunch box]] is often called a lunch pail, or a lunch bucket.\n* Buckets can be reused as seats, tool caddies, hydroponic gardens, chamberpots, \"street\" drums, or livestock feeders\n* Buckets are often used as a children's toys to shape and carry sand on a [[beach]] or in a [[sandpit]]\n\n==Shipping containers==\n{{main|pail (container)}}\nAs a [[shipping container]], the word \"pail\" is a technical term for a bucket shaped package with a sealed top or lid which is used as a [[shipping container]] for chemicals and industrial products.<ref>{{Cite book\n  | last = Soroka\n  | first = W\n  | title = Illustrated Glossary of Packaging Terminology\n  | publisher = Institute of Packaging Professionals\n  | edition = Second\n  | url = http://www.iopp.org/i4a/pages/Index.cfm?pageID=1\n }}</ref>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Hemmoorer Eimer.jpg|Roman bronze [[Situla (vessel)|situla]] from Germany, 2nd-3rd century   \nImage:wooden_bucket.jpg|A wooden bucket\nFile:Feuerl\u00f6scheimer 19 Jh.jpg|German 19th century leather fire-buckets. With wood, leather was the most common material for buckets before modern times\nImage:Man carrying two buckets.JPG|A man carrying two buckets\nImage:Heinrich Zille Wassertr\u00e4gerin.jpg|A young lady carrying a bucket, drawing by German artist [[Heinrich Zille]].\nImage:Janitor's bucket with mop.jpg|A [[mop]] bucket with a [[wringer]].\nImage:Excavator bucket.JPG|An [[excavator bucket]].\nImage:Crusher bucket quarry.jpg|thumb|A [[Crusher#Crusher_Bucket|crusher bucket]]\nImage:AFlex-Monsoon-Bucket.jpg|A [[helicopter bucket]].\nFile:Balde.PNG|Plastic yellow bucket\n\nFile:A metal bucket.jpg|A metal bucket.\n\n</gallery>\n\n==English literature==\nThe bucket has been used in many phrases and idioms in the English language.<ref name=\"Dictionary.com, Idiomatic Phrases related to bucket\">{{cite web | url=http://dictionary.reference.com/idioms/bucket | title=Dictionary.com, Idiomatic Phrases related to bucket | accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Kick the bucket]]: a euphemism for someone's death.\n*Drop the bucket on: which refers to implicating a person.\n*A drop in the bucket: which means a small, inadequate amount when is given in terms of how much is requested or asked.\n*Bucket list: a list of activities one wishes to undertake before death.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bobrinski Bucket]]\n* [[Mop]]\n* [[Pail (container)]]\n* [[There's a Hole in My Bucket]]\n* [[First Data]] Bucket; This term is used for the english word month.  ie bucket one means month one, bucket two month two and so on.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n# Earth Day 2008 article, Fredericksburg, VA, ''Free Lance-Star'' Newspaper [http://fredericksburg.com/News/FLS/2008/042008/04222008/373116]\n# Warning [http://www.cpsc.gov/cpscpub/prerel/prhtml89/89065.html]\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|bucket}}\n{{Commons category|Buckets}}\n* [http://www.hpj.com/archives/2006/mar06/mar6/Five-gallonfarmcollectibles.cfm \"Five-gallon farm collectibles\" by Jennifer M. Latzke]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://fivegallonideas.com/ \"Uses for Five Gallon Buckets]\n* {{youtube|FOo-IwspoWY|\"Utilizing a bucket for self-defense\"}}\n\n{{Cleaning tools}}\n\n[[Category:Containers]]\n[[Category:Food packaging]]\n[[Category:Domestic implements]]"}]}}}}